{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_igglybuff_ver01/data/sn89051213/00414213066/1907101001/0617.xml":{"full_text":"THE QUORUM COURT\nMAKES TAX LEVIES\nAppropriations Made for General Ex\npenses for Ensuing Year\u2014Full\nReport of County Judge\nPrickett.\nThe Polk county quorum court,\ncomposed of the various justices\nof the peace, convened at the\ncourt house at 10 o'clock Monday\nmorning for the purpose of trans\nacting all business coming within\nits jurisdiction.\nThere are twenty-six justices of\nthe peace in the county and of\nthat number eighteen were pres\nent as follows:\nS H Smith and C. Woodruff,\nMina\nI. N. Lane, Potter.\nE. G Turner, Rocky.\nW M. Baxter, Bulger.\nJ. A. Taylor and Emmett Rowe,\nHatfield\nJ. R. Allen. Vandervoort.\nVV VI Darwin, Wickes.\n0. L Gregg. Gr-mniss.\nS J. Gardner and J. R. Crane,\nHartley.\nJ. J. H rnpi- n, Miady\nT J. Wa'ker, Big Fork.\nW. 1'. Gile, In\nJ A. Earl nd Hardy Joins,\nAc- rn.\nA E W at md L P Purvis.\nBoard mp.\nI'hK numtii r beme a auoium\nof the justices of the peace in thi\ncounty, the body at once pro\nceeded to business.\nOrdered by the court that the\nannual reports of the county clerk,\ncounty judge, sheriff and county\ntreasurer be read by the clerk, which\nwas done, and said reports were re\nferred by the court to committees\nappointed as follows:\nClerk\u2019s report\u2014A. E. Wear, I. N.\nLane and J. S. Garner.\nJudge\u2019s report\u2014S. H. Smith, J.\nR. Allen and 0. L. Gregg.\nSheriff\u2019s report\u2014W. M. Baxter, J.\nA. Earl and Hardie Jones.\nTreasurer\u2019s report\u2014C. Woodruff,\nL. P. Purvis and J. R. Crane.\nClerk\u2019s report on school election\u2014\nEmmett Rowe, E. G. Turner and W.\nM. Darwin.\nThe court also appointed the\nfollowing committee on appropri\nations and levy: W. T. Cole, A. E.\nWear and Emmett Rowe.\nAll of the above reports were\napproved.\nOn motion, which carried, the\nfollowing appropriations were made\nfor the ensuing year:\nCircuit courts, $4,000.\nCounty courts, $2,000.\nChancery courts, $100.\nProbate courts, $50.\nMagistrate courts, $250.\nKeeping prisoners, $500.\nAssessment and tax books, $2,000.\nPublic records, $250.\nPublic buildings, $1,000.\nKeeping paupers, $750.\nUnited States judgments, $800.\nBuilding bridges, $4,000.\nFor other lawful expenses, $3,000.\nOn motion, which carried, the\nfollowing tax levies were made for\nthe various state, county, road,\nschool and municipal taxes for the\nyear 1907, to-wit:\nState purposes, general revenue,\n1 3-4 mil la\nCommon schools, 3 mills.\nPension, 1 1-2 mills.\nCapitol, 1-2 mill.\nCounty purposes, general county,\n4 3-4 mills.\nUnited States judgments, 1-4 mill.\nMunicipal tax, city of Mena, 5\nmills.\nMoved and carried that a school\ntax be levied as voted by the various\nschool districts in Polk county and\nreported by the board.\nOn motion, the following levies\nwere made as tax on privileges:\nSaloon and dramshops, $500.\nEach criminal conviction in courts\nof records, $3.\nEach civil suit when verdict ren\ndered by jury courts of record, $3\nEach writ of summons and execu\ntion from courts of record, 50 cents.\nUpon certificates of records of\ndeeds and other instruments of writ\ning, except mortgages, 50 cents.\nUpon certificate of record of each\nmortgage, 15 cents.\nUpon each marriage license is\nsued, 50 cents.\nUpon each sewing machine ped\ndler, $25.\nUpon each circus and menagerie\neach day, $100. Upon each sideshow\ntherewith, $50.\nUpon each exhibition, $5.\nOn motion which carried, that $10\nper day be levied upon each show or\nPublic exhibition given by any street\nfair or carnival.\nThe following is the report of\nbounty Judge Wright Prickett,\nwhich was read by the clerk:\nTo the Honorable Quorum Court,\nPolk County, Arkansas:\nSection 1499 of Kirby\u2019s Digest re\n(|uires a report of certain county\nofficers to this court and in compliance\nwith said section, I herewith submit\nf\u00b0r your consideration the following\nreport with such recommendations\n88 seem advisable.\nRoads and Bridges.\n1 believe that the condition of the\nroads in Polk county are improving\neach year and in my opinion and\njudgment are in better condition to\nday than ever before; although dur\ning the present spring and early\nsummer the heavy rains have given\nthe overseers and the county judge\na great deal of trouble. This, to\ngether with the very heavy traffic in j\nhauling lumber, has made it practi-,\ncally impossible to keep our roads in\ngood condition. The further fact\nthat our road overseers are elected\nrather than appointed by the county j\njudge, has in some instances resulted\nin our not getting as good results\nas we should have done. A feeling\nhas arisen that being elected they\nare not subject to the orders of the\ncounty judge, and consequently a\nlack of harmony prevails. In my\njudgment, in a few instances, the\noverseer is more interested in col- j\nlecting his wages than he is in giv- j\ning the best possible service to his\ndistrict.\nIn this town I have adopted a i.ew\nsystem by way of experiment, that j\nis, by giving one man charge of j\nfrom five to ten miles of road and\nkeeping him constantly employed on\nhis road. I now have two so em\nployed, one man working on the\nroad to Dallas and another I have\nnlaoo/l rtn the Talihina road. I'er\nsons who travel these roads are well\npleased with the results and if the\nexperiment proves successful, I ex\npect to use the same system on each\nroad coming into Mena for a dis\ntance of four to six miles. This\nsystem of improving public roads\noriginated in Massachusetts and is\nbeing used in a number of the New\nEngland states and it is reported\nthat this is the most successful and\nthe cheapest way of keeping roads\nin repair. I hope to extend this\nsystem to other parts of the county.\nThis court at its meeting m Octo\nr ber, 1906, appropriated $5,000 for\nthe building of two steel bridges\nand these bridges are now completed\nand within the next two weeks I\nhope to have the approaches and\nt grading completed so that they can\nbe utilized at that time. All of this\nf appropriation has not been used and\nafter paying for our bridges there\nSSd at least be $2,000 left un\nexpended. There are a number of\nstreams that should be bridged as\ny early as possible. Two in particular\ne I should like to see built next year,\n1 one over Board Camp creek on the\nMena and Hot Springs road and the\nother on the Hatfield and Doaksville\nroad over Mountain Fork river,\ne The first bridge will cos<th\u00ae\nother will probably cost $4,000. I\nwould respectfully recommend that\nin appropriation be made for these\ntwo bridges. The two bridges al\nready built will be half paid for out\nof the funds of Mena special road\ndistrict so that the expense of build\ning will be very light on the county\nfunds.\nPoor Farm and Paupers.\nThe number of paupers cared for\nat public expense and a charge on\nthe county averages nine per month,\nrhis paupers are kept at an expense\nof $7.50 per month, each, exclusive\nof clothing and medical attendance,\nrhere have been eight deaths among\nthe paupers during the past year,\nbut otherwise the health of the\npaupers and their condition have\nbeen good. There are now four\npaupers on the county farm and 1\nrecommend that the same appropri\nation be made for paupers as was\nmade last year.\nPublic Buildings and Property.\n1 have made repairs and improve\nments to the court house and jail to\nthe amount of $1500. Sidewalks\nhave been built on two sides of the\ncourt house square at a cost of $320.\nOur jail is very badly in need of new\ncells as the present ones are practi\ncally worthless and are unsafe to hold\nan ordinary criminal. I believe that\n_\u25a0_-_^ /trtllo uri 11 lui u\nw*v wv..\u00ab\nwaste of money.\nNew cells complete would cost at\nleast $2500 or $3000 and I shall not\nrecommend an appropriation at this\ntime but leave the matter to the\nwisdom of this Honorable Court.\nPublic Records.\nThe public records of this county\nhave been improved by the purchase\nof general indexes during the last\nyear. This has been quite an ex\npense to the county but the law\nspecifically states that the county\ncourt must supply them.\nBloodhounds.\nI have been solicited frequently\nduring the last year to purchase\nbloodhounds for the county, but so\nfar have not done so and leave the\nmatter to the wisdom of this court\nfor determination.\n\u201cArkansas Justice.\u2019\u2019\nI believe that this court should\nauthorize the purchase of a sufficient\nnumber of the \u201cArkansas Justice\u201d\nfor the use of each justice of the\npeace in the county. These will\ncost $5 per volume.\nWolf Scalps.\nSection 8067 of Kirby's Digest\nauthorizes the county court to pay a\npremium on wolf, wild cat and\npanther scalps and at the solicitation\nof quite a number of farmers\nthroughout the county an order was\nmade offering a premium as author\nized by this law. I am not certain\nas to the wisdom of this order and\nrespectfully ask this court for their\njudgment as to whether this order\nshould be continued.\nThis concludes my report and\nrecommendations to this court and\nwith the hope that in our deliber-1\nation we forget selfishness but ap\npropriate, regulate and legislate for\nthe county as a whole regardless of\nany local feeling, they are respect\nfully submitted.\nWright Prickett,\nCounty Judge.\nMENA SHOULD IMPROVE GREATLY\nThe Greatest Need an Organized Ef\nfort by Unselfish Men.\nD. W. Grab tn of Hi iwatha,\nKas., who spent stviral days in\nMena last week in looking after\nthe Graham Clothing Company,\none of his stores, in a conversa\ntion with a representative of The\nStar had much to say regartling\nMena and the business outlook\nhere\nMr. Graham said that thebusi\nness of his Mena store had tn ole\nan increase of 20 p.-r cent during\nthe last year, and he, const quent\nly was greatly pie <sed with the\noutlook. He stated that general\nly his business grew slowly in a\nnew city, hut when once firmly\nestablished he had no f<ar of\nlosing it. He spoke very kind\nof the good service The Si\u00abr had\nrendered in the wa) of advertis\ning.\nMr. Graham said that he con\nsidered Mena a splendid town,\nbut that he felt it could and\nshould he greatly improved, and\nthat its greatest need today was\nan organization of citizens that\nwould work for the city and ex\npect their reward only from the\ngrowth and prosperity of the\ncitv. He said that any member\nof such an organization who at\ntempted to use it for private gain\nmust be set aside if progress be\nmade.\nMr. Graham has a number of\nstores located in different cities\nof the West and has strong ideas\nas to the best methods of build\ning up a town.\nWILL SOON OPEN A\nNEW SLATE QUARRY\nC. B. Baker, a Kansas City Capitalist,\nBuys 160 Acres Near Mena\nSays Mena Needs the \u201cKan\nsas City Spirit.\u201d\nC. B. Baker, a capitalist of\nKansas City, who has been here\nseveral days inspecting the slate\nfie'dseast of town, returned Mon\nday afternoon to his home.\nSo well pleased was Mr. Baker\nwith what he saw that he pur\nchased a 1<>0 acre tract of fine\nslate land about fifteen miles east\nof Mena which contains an im\nmense deposit of black and gra\\\n>late.\nMr. Baker in conversation with\na reporter of The Siai stated that\nne expected to return here in the\nnear fu ure and would commence\nthe development work of opening\nup a quarry. He also stated that\nhe had falleu in love with Men\nand the excellent climate of this\nsection and felt that the future of\nthe town was very bright indeed.\nMr. Baker in speaking of the\nvast deposits of slate in this\ncounty said that the main thim;\n1 I A_ J_I_At-... -I.-I- _\niivv;uv\u00abi iu uv. c i ii lieu ove\ntion of country vas a railroad\nfrom \u2019his place to Hot Spritiys\nHe said not only would the road\nopen up a territori of many rich\nresources, but would be of untoln\nbenefits to the city of Mena and\ntt would be a few years until w> j\nwould have a lv 'ling little cit\nof from 15 000 to 20,000 people.\nHe said that Mena ought to\ncatch the \u201cKansas City spirit\u201d ol\npu-h and progress und intugu\nrate a movement to secure the\nbuilding of this road and never\nlet up until the line is completed\nand in operation.\n$600 -A Bargain if Taken at Once.\n146 acres of fine fruit and\ntruck land, close to Mena and\ng od road. 14 acres in cultiva\ntion. 25 acres in pasture, good\nsix room house, etc. Fine well\nof water and good garden. Over\n100 fruit trees bearing. Call and\nsee me at once over Lochridge\u2019s\nstore. F. M. Reeves.\nd3 wl\nLost\u2014Between Lochridge\u2019s\nstore and Board Camp postoffice,\none bundle containing a skirt and\ndress goods. Finder please re\nturn to M. M. Shields. Mena, or\nDr. Sanford, Board Camp, and\ngreatly oblige Mrs. N. L. Lewis,\nwidow of I. U. Lewis. dwltj\nMen\u2019s $7.50 and $8.50 Suits\nThis line is equally as strong if not stronger\nthan last season. The new browns and greys\nin check and plaids, black worsteds ana the\never popular navy blues. CA tfO CA\nThey are exceptional values dllu\nMen\u2019s $i2.5o Suits\nThere is certainly a great range of patterns and\nmany such beautiful styles from which to\nselect. Any person wanting this price suit\nshould not fail to see our $12.50 line. CA\nOur Specials at.\nL CHRI I E SI\nCLOTHING STORE\nW E are prepared to show you this fall I!\nthe largest stock of Men's, Youth\u2019s,\nand Boys' Clothing ev er .sh v\\ u in P >lk\ncounty, and it was bought from the largest\nmanufacturers in America and at the low\nest possible price for spot cash.\nI he first time u is convenient call at\nour store and we will take pleasure in\nshowing you the New Styles and Correct\nFit ot our Clothing.\nr*>\nMen\u2019s $10.00 Suits\nHere is the black and brown Meltons, good,\nwell tailored worsteds. Correct in pattern,\nquality and style. A Suit equal in many re\nspects to most $15.00 suits. <t1A AA\nOur price.tpllMFV\nMen